{"type":"tool_result","timestamp":"2026-03-05T14:40:18.983Z","tool_id":"run_shell_command_1772721612691_0","status":"success","output":"[\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-cvm\",\n    \"title\": \"Add GitHub Actions CI workflow\",\n    \"description\": \"Add a GitHub Actions CI workflow at .github/workflows/ci.yml. The workflow should run on push and pull_request to main.\\n\\nJobs (all on ubuntu-latest, Go version from go.mod):\\n1. build - go build ./...\\n2. vet - go vet ./...\\n3. test - go test ./... (once Forge-tqb adds tests; initially just verifies compilation)\\n4. golangci-lint (optional, use golangci/golangci-lint-action) - catches formatting and common issues\\n\\nWorkflow triggers:\\n  on:\\n    push:\\n      branches: [main]\\n    pull_request:\\n      branches: [main]\\n\\nKey requirements:\\n- Use actions/checkout@v4 and actions/setup-go@v5 with cache: true\\n- Store Go cache between runs (setup-go handles this automatically with cache: true)\\n- Fail fast on build/vet before running tests\\n- The workflow filename should be ci.yml; the workflow name \\\"CI\\\"\\n- Add a status badge to README.md once it is green\\n\\nNote: There is no Makefile currently. The CI should use plain go commands, not make targets.\\nNo release or publish step needed here - this is only for PR validation and branch protection.\\r\\n\",\n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 1,\n    \"issue_type\": \"task\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:26:45Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:26:45Z\",\n    \"dependencies\": [\n      {\n        \"issue_id\": \"Forge-cvm\",\n        \"depends_on_id\": \"Forge-tqb\",\n        \"type\": \"discovered-from\",\n        \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:26:48Z\",\n        \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n        \"metadata\": \"{}\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-yld\",\n    \"title\": \"Add unit tests for core packages\",\n    \"description\": \"Add unit tests for Forge's core packages. The codebase currently has no test files.\\n\\nPriority packages to cover (in order):\\n1. internal/config - config loading, validation, defaults, poll_interval parsing, env var override\\n2. internal/poller - mock bd output, priority sorting, per-anvil merge, error handling\\n3. internal/smith - readStreamJSON: parse Claude/Gemini stream-json events, rate_limit_event, result event stats\\n4. internal/provider - BuildArgs output for each provider, Defaults() ordering\\n5. internal/ghpr - PRStatus methods (IsMerged, NeedsChanges, CIsPassing, HasApproval)\\n6. internal/bellows - snapshot diff logic: that events fire on transitions, not on repeat state\\n\\nTest conventions:\\n- Use t.TempDir() for any filesystem work\\n- Use table-driven tests ([]struct{name, input, want}) throughout\\n- Mock external processes (bd, gh, claude, gemini) by swapping the exec.Command function or using a test binary approach\\n- No integration tests that require live network/credentials\\n- Place tests in the same package (_test suffix files) or a separate _test package where internal access is needed\\r\\n\",\n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 1,\n    \"issue_type\": \"task\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:26:13Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:26:13Z\",\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-ibz\",\n    \"title\": \"Hearth Workers view: show active component per worker (smith/temper/warden/bellows)\",\n    \"description\": \"In Hearth Workers panel each row shows a bead/worker entry but does not indicate which Forge component is currently active for it (Smith writing code, Temper running checks, Bellows monitoring, Warden reviewing). Fix: add a component indicator column or tag to each worker row. The worker state in the state DB tracks status (running, pending, done, failed) but not the active sub-component. Options: (1) Store the active component name in the workers table (e.g. a new phase column: smith|temper|warden|bellows|idle) and update it at each pipeline phase transition in pipeline.go and bellows.go. (2) Alternatively derive it from the event log: the most recent event for that bead ID implies the phase. Display in the Workers panel as a short tag e.g. [smith] [temper] [warden] alongside the bead ID and status. Color coding: smith=yellow (writing), temper=cyan (checking), warden=magenta (reviewing), bellows=blue (monitoring).\\r\\n\",      \n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 2,\n    \"issue_type\": \"feature\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:38:06Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:38:06Z\",\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-e28\",\n    \"title\": \"Hearth event log: wrap message text instead of truncating\",       \n    \"description\": \"In Hearth TUI, the Events panel truncates event messages to a short single line, forcing the user to open log files to see what happened. Fix: increase visible text per row substantially (target 200+ chars). Wrap onto multiple lines based on actual panel width rather than hard-truncation. Timestamp and event type prefix stay compact; only the message body wraps. Ensure the list/viewport component height allows 2-3 lines per event when wrapping. Affects internal/hearth/ Bubbletea TUI code.\\r\\n\",\n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 2,\n    \"issue_type\": \"feature\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:37:49Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:37:49Z\",\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-wld\",\n    \"title\": \"Hearth event log: show full message text instead of truncating\",  \n    \"description\": \"In the Hearth TUI, the Events panel truncates event message text to a single short\\nline. This forces the user to open log files manually to see what actually happened.\\n\\nFix: Increase the visible text per event row substantially. The Events panel should\\nshow enough of the message that common cases (e.g. warden verdict, Smith summary,\\nCI failure reason, error text) are readable in-place.\\n\\nImplementation notes:\\n- internal/hearth/ contains the Bubbletea TUI\\n- The Events panel renders rows from the state DB event log (db.ListEvents or similar)\\n- Increase the per-row character limit from whatever it currently is to at least 200\\n  characters (or ideally wrap onto a second line if the panel height allows)\\n- If the panel uses a fixed column width, derive the wrap width dynamically from\\n  the actual panel width (m.width or equivalent) so it adapts to terminal size\\n- For the event body/message field specifically: prefer wrapping over hard truncation\\n  so the user can see the full content by scrolling within the panel\\n- If a viewport or list component is used, ensure its height is sufficient to show\\n  2-3 lines per event when text wraps\\n- The timestamp + event type prefix can stay compact; only the message body should wrap\\r\\n\",      \n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 2,\n    \"issue_type\": \"feature\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:37:36Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:37:36Z\",\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-4ei\",\n    \"title\": \"Configurable per-anvil auto-dispatch behavior\",\n    \"description\": \"Currently Forge dispatches ALL ready beads from 'bd ready --json' automatically. Add configurable control over which beads get auto-dispatched, on a per-anvil basis.\\n\\nNew per-anvil config fields (in AnvilConfig in internal/config/config.go):\\n  auto_dispatch: all | tagged | priority | off\\n    - all: current behavior, dispatch everything ready (default)\\n    - tagged: only dispatch beads whose 'tags' field contains auto_dispatch_tag\\n    - priority: only dispatch beads at or above auto_dispatch_min_priority\\n    - off: never auto-dispatch; beads only run via 'forge queue run \\u003cid\\u003e'\\n  auto_dispatch_tag: string  (used when auto_dispatch: tagged, e.g. 'forge-auto')\\n  auto_dispatch_min_priority: int  (used when auto_dispatch: priority, e.g. 1 means P0+P1 only)\\n\\nImplementation notes:\\n- Add Tags []string json:'tags' to poller.Bead (bd ready JSON may include a tags array; if absent, tags-mode falls through to dispatch nothing).\\n- Add the new fields to AnvilConfig with defaults (auto_dispatch defaults to 'all').\\n- Apply the filter after polling in poller.Poll or in daemon.go before dispatching.\\n- Validate the config: if auto_dispatch=tagged, auto_dispatch_tag must be non-empty; if auto_dispatch=priority, min_priority must be 0-4.\\n- Update forge.yaml sample/docs with the new knobs.\\n- The 'off' mode is useful for repos where Forge should observe beads but never touch them without explicit human invocation.\",\n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 2,\n    \"issue_type\": \"feature\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:16:54Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:16:54Z\",\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-olo\",\n    \"title\": \"Parse and log Gemini stats from result event\",\n    \"description\": \"Gemini's stream-json result event does not have a 'total_cost_usd' field but does include a 'stats' object: {total_tokens, input_tokens, output_tokens, cached, input, duration_ms, tool_calls}. Currently readStreamJSON only reads TotalCostUSD so Gemini runs always show cost=0 and token counts=0. Fix: add a Stats field to StreamEvent matching Gemini's stats shape, populate CostUSD (Gemini has no cost but we can estimate from token counts if desired, or just leave 0), populate TokensIn/TokensOut from stats.input_tokens/output_tokens, and log the full stats summary (tokens, cache hits, tool_calls, duration_ms) to the smith log file and to an EventInfo so it appears in forge history output.\",    \n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 2,\n    \"issue_type\": \"task\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:06:51Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:06:51Z\",\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"Forge-ebr\",\n    \"title\": \"Add event logging to warden, temper, and bellows\",\n    \"description\": \"Currently the warden, temper, and bellows components do not emit any structured events to the state DB event log. Add db.LogEvent calls at key lifecycle points: warden should log when it starts a review (EventInfo with bead ID) and when it finishes (EventInfo with verdict + summary). Temper should log when it starts checks, and when it passes or fails. Bellows should log when it starts monitoring, finds CI failures, or posts review fix comments. Follow the existing pattern in daemon.go and pipeline.go.\",\n    \"status\": \"open\",\n    \"priority\": 2,\n    \"issue_type\": \"task\",\n    \"owner\": \"Robin.Edvard.Smith@fhi.no\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:06:29Z\",\n    \"created_by\": \"Robin Smith\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-05T14:06:29Z\",\n    \"dependency_count\": 0,\n    \"dependent_count\": 0,\n    \"comment_count\": 0\n  }\n]"}
